    {
      "id": "15b36f45-6887-ef11-8474-000d3a37e3b6",
      "type": "GeneralText",
      "area": "General",
      "position": 1,
      "content": "DATED MATERIAL, SUBJECT TO CHANGE. PLEASE CONSULT CURRENT UCSD GENERAL CATALOG FOR ANY ADDITIONAL INFORMATION. Special Advising Note: All students must do a placement interview before enrolling in their first Mandarin Chinese course at UCSD. Instructions for the interview can be located at the Chinese Studies Program website: http://chinesestudies.ucsd.edu/language/placement-info.html Chinese Studies is an interdisciplinary program that allows the student interested in China to utilize the university's offerings in various departments to build a major leading to a B.A. degree. The student choosing a major in Chinese Studies must meet the following requirements. Two years of Mandarin Chinese (CHIN 10 A-B-C and CHIN 20 A-B-C ) or equivalent Chinese knowledge. Twelve upper-division four-unit courses in Chinese studies topics. a. Courses must be taken from at least three departments or programs. b. Three of the twelve courses must be upper-division Chinese history. c. No more than six of the upper-division courses may be language acquisition courses. d. A minimum of six upper-division courses must be taken at UCSD. 3. As a rule, all courses must be taken and completed for a letter grade for both the major and minor. Exceptions are granted for CHIN 198 and CHIN 199. NOTE: One year of Community College course work equals three quarters of UCSD course work. For more information please visit https://chinesestudies.ucsd.edu/undergraduate/major.html",
      "contentHtml": "<p><strong>DATED MATERIAL, SUBJECT TO CHANGE. PLEASE CONSULT CURRENT UCSD GENERAL CATALOG FOR ANY ADDITIONAL INFORMATION. </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(169, 62, 58);\">Special Advising Note: </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong>All students must do a placement interview before enrolling in their first Mandarin Chinese course at UCSD. Instructions for the interview can be located at the Chinese Studies Program website: </strong><a href=\"http://chinesestudies.ucsd.edu/language/placement-info.html\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>http://chinesestudies.ucsd.edu/language/placement-info.html</strong></a><strong> </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong>Chinese Studies is an interdisciplinary program that allows the student interested in China to utilize the university's offerings in various departments to build a major leading to a B.A. degree. The student choosing a major in Chinese Studies must meet the following requirements. </strong></p><ol><li><strong>Two years of Mandarin Chinese (CHIN 10 A-B-C and CHIN 20 A-B-C ) or equivalent Chinese knowledge.</strong></li><li><strong>Twelve upper-division four-unit courses in Chinese studies topics. </strong></li></ol><p class=\"ql-indent-1\"><strong> a. Courses must be taken from at least three departments or programs. </strong></p><p class=\"ql-indent-1\"><strong> b. Three of the twelve courses must be upper-division Chinese history. </strong></p><p class=\"ql-indent-1\"><strong>c. No more than six of the upper-division courses may be language acquisition courses. </strong></p><p class=\"ql-indent-1\"><strong>d. A minimum of six upper-division courses must be taken at UCSD. </strong></p><p><strong> 3. As a rule, all courses must be taken and completed for a letter grade for both the major and minor. Exceptions are granted for CHIN 198 and CHIN 199. </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(169, 62, 58);\">NOTE: One year of Community College course work equals three quarters of UCSD course work. </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong>For more information please visit </strong><a href=\"https://chinesestudies.ucsd.edu/undergraduate/major.html\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>https://chinesestudies.ucsd.edu/undergraduate/major.html</strong></a></p>"
    },
    {
